tances during the indemnitor's ownership or operations, violations of environmental laws, and all remediation costs regardless of when discovered. The indemnification should extend to regulatory enforcement actions, third-party claims, natural resource damages, and diminution in property value. Specify that the indemnity covers both known and unknown conditions, and survives regardless of the indemnitee's knowledge or due diligence findings. Research current environmental indemnity standards to ensure the scope reflects market practice for similar transactions.\n\n**Representations, Warranties, and Covenants**: Include comprehensive representations regarding environmental compliance history, absence of known violations or pending investigations, no undisclosed releases or contamination, and full disclosure of all environmental reports and assessments. Representations should address permits, underground storage tanks, asbestos, lead-based paint, and hazardous materials storage or use. Draft ongoing covenants requiring continued compliance with all environmental laws, immediate notice of any violations or governmental communications, maintenance of necessary permits, cooperation with investigations, and granting access for environmental assessments. If uploaded documents contain site-specific environmental data or Phase I findings, incorporate appropriate qualifications or disclosures while maintaining the indemnitor's liability.\n\n**Survival, Duration, and Enforcement Mechanisms**: Specify that all indemnification obligations survive the closing of the underlying transaction and continue until the later of loan repayment, property transfer, or completion of any required remediation. Environmental liabilities can emerge decades after a transaction, so the survival period should reflect the long-tail nature of environmental risks. Address whether the indemnity is absolute and unconditional, independent of any loan default, and enforceable regardless of bankruptcy or i